s the standardisation status of the regionally official and minority languages are discussed. Language borrowing, code switching and other language contact phenomena are analysed in detail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGermanic languagesxSocial aspectsxEurope. 0aGermanic languagesxSocial aspects. 0aLanguages in contactxEurope. 0aLanguages in contactzEurope. 0aRomance languagesxSocial aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh1 aBister-Broosen, Helga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarquennes, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurme, Luc van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichinger, Ludwig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehlen, Fernand, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelde, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRash, Felicity, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRyckeboer, Hugo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreffers-Daller, Jeanine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreffers-Daller, Jeanine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWillemyns, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWillemyns, Roland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066313608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060671340uhttps://doi.org/10.21832/978185359671140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781853596711